The Ash Requiem is Rakuen's recurring memorial rite for orchard loss and cistern poisoning during the Ash-and-Iron years.
It is distinct from Kowloon's Ashfall Vigil: the Vigil commemorates the founding moment, while the Requiem commemorates ongoing loss across the years of sustained catastrophe.
The Requiem is held at the Bloom Pavilion — Rakuen's civic center — at the end of the agricultural season, timed to the final harvest count rather than a fixed calendar date.
Each year the Requiem reads from a ledger of the preceding year's agricultural failures alongside the founding-era orchard loss record, placing current shortage in historical continuity with the Ash-and-Iron devastation.
The Bloom Council officiates the reading; the Garden Ledger Clerks provide the figures.
Cisterns are tested during the Requiem period and results posted publicly — a practice originating in the Ash-and-Iron years when sulfur contamination of wells went undetected in several settlements before casualties accumulated.
The Requiem does not name individuals; it names orchards, water sources, and route segments — the infrastructure that failed, rather than the people who died in the failure.
This naming convention was contested in the early Requiem years and remains contested by some: the argument is that naming infrastructure erases the people lost with it.
The counter-argument from the Compact Purist faction is that naming people in memorial to Midgaard (as the Ash Plea did) politicizes grief; naming infrastructure keeps the Requiem internal.
The Ash Requiem is Rakuen's most stable civic institution: it has been held without interruption since the founding generation, through all three annexation petition cycles and their political fractures.

