The Requiem was established by the founding Bloom Council before the formal Rakuen charter was ratified — it predates the city's legal structure. The founding text states: "Count what the ash took. Count it again next year. Count it until there is nothing left to count, or until what was taken is returned." The "returned" has been interpreted for generations: the Assimilation League reads it as annexation to Midgaard's supply system; Compact Purists as reconstruction of Rakuen's own agricultural capacity; Quiet Separatists as maritime independence. The Garden Ledger Clerks read none of these at the Requiem — they read only the figures. The Requiem's cistern-testing protocol was the practical origin of Rakuen's environmental monitoring infrastructure. The Bloom Pavilion's memorial wall has founding-era orchard names now barely legible, worn by decades of weather the designers did not anticipate; whether to restore them or leave them is contested along the same political axes as everything else.

